---
/** Hub: seller profit + tax. Worked example by sellerProfit(). */
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import SellerProfitCalculator from '../../components/calculators/SellerProfitCalculator.tsx';
import { sellerProfit } from '../../lib/se-business';
import { formatMoney, formatPct } from '../../lib/tax-engine';

const ex = sellerProfit(50000, 15000, 5000, 2000, 1000, 'OH', 'single');
---

<Base
  title="Seller profit calculator 2026 — Etsy, eBay, Shopify"
  description="Turn online sales into real profit and take-home: revenue less cost of goods, fees and shipping, then self-employment and income tax. Any marketplace."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="hero-label">2026 tax year</p>
    <h1>Seller profit calculator</h1>
    <p class="tagline">Your sales total isn't your income. Cost of goods, fees and shipping come out first.</p>
  </section>

  <p>
    Selling on Etsy, eBay, Shopify or any marketplace, your taxable income is
    profit, not revenue. Cost of goods sold, platform and payment fees, and shipping
    all come off first — then self-employment tax and income tax apply to what is
    left. This shows your profit, your margin, and your real take-home.
  </p>

  <SellerProfitCalculator client:load defaultRevenue={50000} defaultFees={5000} />

  <h2>Worked example — {formatMoney(50000)} in sales</h2>
  <p>
    An Ohio seller does {formatMoney(50000)} in sales with {formatMoney(15000)} cost
    of goods, {formatMoney(5000)} in fees, {formatMoney(2000)} shipping and
    {formatMoney(1000)} other costs:
  </p>
  <table class="data-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Line</th><th>Amount</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Revenue</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.revenue)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Total expenses</td><td>− {formatMoney(ex.totalExpenses)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Net profit</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.netProfit)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Net margin</td><td>{formatPct(ex.netMargin)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Self-employment + income tax</td><td>− {formatMoney(ex.totalTax)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Take-home</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.takeHome)}</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    The {formatMoney(50000)} of sales is really {formatMoney(ex.netProfit)} of profit
    — a {formatPct(ex.netMargin)} margin — and {formatMoney(ex.takeHome)} of take-home
    after tax. Being taxed on revenue instead of profit would roughly double the bill,
    which is why tracking cost of goods sold matters more than any other number here.
  </p>

  <h2>Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>What is cost of goods sold for a seller?</h3>
    <p>
      What the items you sold cost you. For resale it is the purchase price; for
      handmade goods it is materials (and sometimes a labor allocation); for
      print-on-demand it is the base product cost. It is deducted only when the item
      sells, and it is usually a seller's largest deduction.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Are platform fees deductible?</h3>
    <p>
      Fully. Etsy listing and transaction fees, eBay final-value fees, Shopify
      subscription and payment processing, Amazon referral and FBA fees — all are
      100% deductible business expenses. So are shipping supplies and postage.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Do I owe tax if I sold personal items?</h3>
    <p>
      Selling your own used things at a loss is not taxable and the loss is not
      deductible. Selling them at a gain is taxable. Buying to resell is a business —
      that is what this calculator models. If your 1099-K mixes personal and business
      sales, separate them.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Why is my 1099-K higher than my profit?</h3>
    <p>
      Because it reports gross payments — including the fees, refunds and shipping
      that never became profit. Reconcile it down with the
      <a href="/1099-k-calculator/">1099-K calculator</a> so you are taxed on profit,
      not on money that passed through.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>Related tools</h2>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    <li><a href="/1099-k-calculator/">1099-K reconciliation calculator</a></li>
    <li><a href="/gig-tax-calculator/">Gig tax by category</a> — sellers, drivers, creators</li>
    <li><a href="/quarterly-tax-calculator/">Quarterly tax calculator</a> — paying as you go</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="results-note">
    Estimate for the 2026 tax year using the standard deduction. Pick your state for
    the state tax line. Not tax advice.
  </p>
</Base>
